  "prompt": "What is the procedure to apply to an RTI?",
  "response": "The procedure to file a Right to Information (RTI) application in India is relatively straightforward. Here's a step-by-step guide:\n\n1. **Determine the Relevant Public Authority**: Identify the public authority to which you want to apply for information. This could be a government department, ministry, or other public bodies.\n\n2. **Draft the Application**: Prepare your RTI application. Your application should include:\n   - Your name and contact information (address, phone number, and email).\n   - A clear statement that you are requesting information under the RTI Act.\n   - Specific details of the information you seek, framed in a way that it can be easily understood.\n   - Mention the format in which you would prefer to receive the information (such as printed copy, electronic format, etc.).\n   - The relevant public authority\u2019s name and address.\n\n3. **Payment of Fees**: There is often a nominal fee for filing an RTI application, which varies based on the state or central government rules. Usually, it is \u20b910 for a central RTI application. You can pay this fee through different modes, such as:\n   - Cash (in person, if applicable).\n   - Demand Draft (DD).\n   - Indian Postal Order (IPO).\n   - Banker's cheque.\n   Check the specific authority\u2019s payment details.\n\n4. **Submission of the Application**: Submit your application either online (if the public authority has an online RTI portal) or in person/by post. If submitting online, ensure that you fill the necessary fields in the online form.\n\n5. **Obtain Receipt**: If you submit the application in person, ensure that you get an acknowledgment receipt with a unique application number. This will help you track the status of your application.\n\n6. **Await Response**: The public authority is required to respond to your RTI application within 30 days (or 48 hours for life or liberty-related queries). Keep track of the time.\n\n7. **Receive Information**: The information will be sent to you in the format you specified, or you may be informed if the information cannot be provided.\n\n8. **Appeal Process**: If your application is denied, or you are not satisfied with the information provided, you have the right to file an appeal against the decision. The first appeal should be made to a higher authority within the same public authority.\n\n9. **Second Appeal**: If still unsatisfied after the first appeal, you can escalate the matter to the Central Information Commission (CIC) or State Information Commission (SIC), depending on whether your request was submitted to a central or state public authority.\n\nRemember to keep a copy of your RTI application and any correspondence for your records.",
